<br>
Nimm, I think that's definition of &quot;Equipping yourself.&quot;  If you contributed just as much to a fight and you've won the roll, that doesn't make you greedy.  It (should) just mean that you need an upgrade just as much as the next guy.  Just because ItemX drops and the guy next to me could wear it now and I'd have to sell it (ick) to afford an equivalent upgrade, that doesn't make someone greedy.  It just means the other guy would've been more convenienced. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#3B3B3B><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub35.ezboard.com/ustrykninedshiv.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Stryknine DShiv</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br> <font color=#FF0000>(3/6/02 6:34:40 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub35.ezboard.com/fthesafehouseloungegeneraldiscussion.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=22643.topic&index=33>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Well, at least SOME people here get the point.</span><hr size=1> Thanks guys. I didnt even mention a RBG in my arguements, but again claiming &quot;NBG&quot; on something like that is just going to cause even more problems- Would my Rogue wear it? Yes. Would I get more use from it than a SK in the group? No. Would I get more use than a Wizard? probably. So, who 'needs' it and gets to roll?  (Yes, I have been in this situation. The SK had a nice belt they just won in Kael so they were going to award ME the RBG because we were the only 2 melee in the group. I said &quot;I actually need the STR from my TBB, and would probably just sell the belt. So, open roll for it&quot;. We did, mage won (and gave to a Warrior friend who needed it).  A week later, that warrior won a Heiro cloak in the crypt- and the mage was thrilled to be given the item.<br>
(I knew the Mage that won the RBG, and the Warrior who ended up with it. I don't remember who the others in the group were, but it was mostly pickup group).<br>
<br>
If I were in Karnors with 5 complete strangers, and a pair of Mrylokar guantlets dropped, I would never DREAM of demanding to be given the gloves. THAT IMO is greedy. ld take my chances like the rest of them, Hope Bristlebain smiled on me and I won, and if not, I'd hopefully get lucky on the next item that dropped, so I could sell it and buy them from the guy with the gloves. Thats how the economy in EQ works.<br>
<br>
If I were in karnors with 5 good friends and the gloves dropped, and they didn't give them to me, well, Id be pissed. But that is where the difference lies- but I don't think Nimbull draws that distinction.<br>
<br>
*By the way.. before calling me greedy (which you have done on several occasions), how about stop over on bertoxxolus and ask people who know me or my Enchanter (Poxx) how 'greedy' I am.  <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#2f2f4f><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub35.ezboard.com/umeyekal.showPublicProfile?language=EN>meyekal</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br> <font color=#FF0000>(3/6/02 7:33:52 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub35.ezboard.com/fthesafehouseloungegeneraldiscussion.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=22643.topic&index=38>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> -</span><hr size=1> I thought the example given were everyone rolls, and you can re-roll if you give up your previous win is the best way to do it.  I'm not exactly sure how it would be handled with people leaving and joining the group though.<br>
<br>
Bottom line is that all loot has some value in plat.  The actual item itself should be ignored, and it should be thought of as a big fat purse of coins.  If an item is droppable, then whoever wants that item can also buy that same item.  It's just like pooling all the money together that drops and lottoing it off, it might not be the best way, but it is the fairest.<br>
